	<a name="84343806">&nbsp;</a><br>
	<h1>Unicode Special Symbols</h1>There are some character entities and character codes that are needed for presenting mathematical work, even when the demands for symbology are as simple as for Miser.&nbsp;  Here are the key symbols to be used.<h2>Basic Character Entities</h2>These entities are for the standard "first-page" of Unicode, which is available by default.<h3>ISO 646 character entities</h3>The pure ISO 646 (sometimes called ASCII) characters are encoded in 7 bits, with the high-order bit always 0.&nbsp;  Four of these codes can require alternative character entities so that there is no confusion with the markup elements.&nbsp;  These entities can be expressed numerically (that is, by the number of their ISO 646 and Unicode UTF-8 code) or as special named entities:<br /><br /><pre><br />&amp;#34;    &amp;quot;    &#34;    &quot;<br />&amp;#38;    &amp;amp;     &#38;    &amp;<br />&amp;#60;    &amp;lt;      &#60;    &lt;<br />&amp;#62;    &amp;gt;      &#62;    &gt;<br /></pre><br /><br />Notice that the code numbers are in decimal.&nbsp;  These are sometimes shown with a leading 0, but it doesn't matter.&nbsp; In the table, the actual characters are produced to the right of the character entities using the respective entity forms.<h3>ISO 8859-1 Latin-1 supplement character entities</h3>Although HTML is often coded using direct insertion of 8-bit character codes (that is, codes in the range &amp;#128 to &amp;#255), and these codes are recognized as being in some appropriate character set encoding by browsers, these codes are not safe to use across character-set encoding systems.&nbsp;  The safest way to specify those additional characters is with character entities, when defined, and with Unicode numeric codes when not defined.<br /><br />Here are the the codes for the graphical and control extensions that are defined for use with XHTML:<br /><br /><pre><br />&amp;#160;    &amp;nbsp;    &#160;    &nbsp;    non-breaking space (you can't see it here)<br />&amp;#161;    &amp;iexcl;   &#161;    &iexcl;    inverted exclamation point<br />&amp;#162;    &amp;cent;    &#162;    &cent;    cent sign<br />&amp;#163;    &amp;pound;   &#163;    &pound;    pound (sterling) sign<br />&amp;#164;    &amp;curren;  &#164;    &curren;    general currency sign<br />&amp;#165;    &amp;yen;     &#165;    &yen;    yen sign<br />&amp;#166;    &amp;brvbar;  &#166;    &brvbar;    broken vertical bar<br />&amp;#167;    &amp;sect;    &#167;    &sect;    section sign [Miser: computationally-determined symbol]<br />&amp;#168;    &amp;uml;     &#168;    &uml;    umlaut<br />&amp;#169;    &amp;copy;    &#169;    &copy;    copyright symbol<br />&amp;#170;    &amp;ordf;    &#170;    &ordf;    feminine ordinal<br />&amp;#171;    &amp;laquo;   &#171;    &laquo;    left double angle quote <br />&amp;#172;    &amp;not;     &#172;    &not;    not sign<br />&amp;#173;    &amp;shy;     &#173;    &shy;    soft (discretionary) hyphen [may not appear]<br />&amp;#174;    &amp;reg;     &#174;    &reg;    registered trademark symbol<br />&amp;#175;    &amp;macr;    &#175;    &macr;    macron accent<br /><br />&amp;#176;    &amp;deg;     &#176;    &deg;    degree sign<br />&amp;#177;    &amp;plusmn;  &#177;    &plusmn;    plus-or-minus sign<br />&amp;#178;    &amp;sup2;    &#178;    &sup2;    superscript 2<br />&amp;#179;    &amp;sup3;    &#179;    &sup3;    superscript 3<br />&amp;#180;    &amp;acute;   &#180;    &acute;    acute accent<br />&amp;#181;    &amp;micro;   &#181;    &micro;    micro sign (Greek mu)<br />&amp;#182;    &amp;para;    &#182;    &para;    paragraph sign [Miser: &lt;ob> well-ordering relation]<br />&amp;#183;    &amp;middot;  &#183;    &middot;    middle dot<br />&amp;#184;    &amp;cedil;   &#184;    &cedil;    cedilla<br />&amp;#185;    &amp;sup1;    &#185;    &sup1;    superscript 1<br />&amp;#186;    &amp;ordm;    &#186;    &ordm;    masculine ordinal<br />&amp;#187;    &amp;raquo;   &#187;    &raquo;    right double-angle quote<br />&amp;#188;    &amp;frac14;  &#188;    &frac14;    fraction one-fourth<br />&amp;#189;    &amp;frac12;  &#189;    &frac12;    fraction one-half<br />&amp;#190;    &amp;frac34;  &#190;    &frac34;    fraction three-fourths<br />&amp;#191;    &amp;iquest;  &#191;    &iquest;    inverted question mark<br /><br /> . . .<br />&amp;#215;    &amp;times;   &#215;    &times;    multiplication (times) sign<br />&amp;#216;    &amp;Oslash;  &#216;    &Oslash;    Capital O, slash<br /><br /> . . .<br />&amp;#247;    &amp;divide;  &#247;    &divide;    division sign<br />&amp;#248;    &amp;oslash;  &#248;    &oslash;    Small o, slash<br /></pre><br /><br />There are additional characters in the range &amp;#192 to &amp;#255.&nbsp;  These are all special forms of letters, and they are most-often used in bibliographic citations and the correct spelling of names (e.g, G&ouml;del).&nbsp;  The entity names are systematic (e.g., &amp;ouml; for &ouml;, &amp;Ouml; for &Ouml;, and &amp;eacute; for &eacute;).&nbsp;  These names should be used instead of direct entry of the characters, and they are simple to learn with practice.<br /><br />I have listed, above, only those special symbols of the Latin-1 supplement that may be useful in formulae or adapted to specialized symbolic purposes.  <br /><br />Users of Microsoft Windows character sets will recognize that there are additional special characters available within the 8-bit code of the platform.&nbsp;  The characters corresponding to these codes are also useful, but the codes are not appropriate to use in what is intended to be UTF-8 encoding for Unicodes.&nbsp; The trick is to find designations in Unicode or at least having defined character entities.<h3>ISO 8859-7 and the Greek letters</h3>Unicode provides for Greek and Coptic alphabets as they are used.&nbsp;  This goes beyond the typical use of the Greek alphabet in mathematical symbology, so I wil not attempt to portray all of the characters.<br /><br />The unicode table for Greek characters based on ISO 8859-7 begins at U+0370, decimal code position #880.&nbsp;  The code block is not fully used.&nbsp;  Here are the selections, with their character entity names, that are most-commonly used as mathematical symbols:<br /><pre><br /> . . .<br />&amp;#913;    &amp;Alpha;   &#913;    &Alpha;    Greek capital alpha<br />&amp;#914;    &amp;Beta;    &#914;    &Beta;    Greek capital beta<br />&amp;#915;    &amp;Gamma;   &#915;    &Gamma;    Greek capital gamma<br />&amp;#916;    &amp;Delta;   &#916;    &Delta;    Greek capital delta<br />&amp;#917;    &amp;Epsilon; &#917;    &Epsilon;    Greek capital epsilon<br />&amp;#918;    &amp;Zeta;    &#918;    &Zeta;    Greek capital zeta<br />&amp;#919;    &amp;Eta;     &#919;    &Eta;    Greek capital eta<br />&amp;#920;    &amp;Theta;   &#920;    &Theta;    Greek capital theta<br />&amp;#921;    &amp;Iota;    &#921;    &Iota;    Greek capital iota<br />&amp;#922;    &amp;Kappa;   &#922;    &Kappa;    Greek capital kappa<br />&amp;#923;    &amp;Lambda;  &#923;    &Lambda;    Greek capital lambda<br />&amp;#924;    &amp;Mu;      &#924;    &Mu;    Greek capital mu<br />&amp;#925;    &amp;Nu;      &#925;    &Nu;    Greek capital nu<br />&amp;#926;    &amp;Xi;      &#926;    &Xi;    Greek capital xi<br />&amp;#927;    &amp;Omicron; &#927;    &Omicron;    Greek capital omicron<br /><br />&amp;#928;    &amp;Pi;      &#928;    &Pi;    Greek capital pi<br />&amp;#929;    &amp;Rho;     &#929;    &Rho;    Greek capital rho<br /> . . .<br />&amp;#931;    &amp;Sigma;   &#931;    &Sigma;    Greek capital sigma<br />&amp;#932;    &amp;Tau;     &#932;    &Tau;    Greek capital tau<br />&amp;#933;    &amp;Upsilon; &#933;    &Upsilon;    Greek capital upsilon<br />&amp;#934;    &amp;Phi;     &#934;    &Phi;    Greek capital phi<br />&amp;#935;    &amp;Chi;     &#935;    &Chi;    Greek capital chi<br />&amp;#936;    &amp;Psi;     &#936;    &Psi;    Greek capital psi<br />&amp;#937;    &amp;Omega;   &#937;    &Omega;    Greek capital omega<br /><br /> . . .<br />&amp;#945;    &amp;alpha;   &#945;    &alpha;    Greek small letter alpha<br />&amp;#946;    &amp;beta;    &#946;    &beta;    Greek small letter beta<br />&amp;#947;    &amp;gamma;   &#947;    &gamma;    Greek small letter gamma<br />&amp;#948;    &amp;delta;   &#948;    &delta;    Greek small letter delta<br />&amp;#949;    &amp;epsilon; &#949;    &epsilon;    Greek small letter epsilon<br />&amp;#950;    &amp;zeta;    &#950;    &zeta;    Greek small letter zeta<br />&amp;#951;    &amp;eta;     &#951;    &eta;    Greek small letter eta<br />&amp;#952;    &amp;theta;   &#952;    &theta;    Greek small letter theta<br />&amp;#953;    &amp;iota;    &#953;    &iota;    Greek small letter iota<br />&amp;#954;    &amp;kappa;   &#954;    &kappa;    Greek small letter kappa<br />&amp;#955;    &amp;lambda;  &#955;    &lambda;    Greek small letter lambda<br />&amp;#956;    &amp;mu;      &#956;    &mu;    Greek small letter mu<br />&amp;#957;    &amp;nu;      &#957;    &nu;    Greek small letter nu<br />&amp;#958;    &amp;xi;      &#958;    &xi;    Greek small letter xi<br />&amp;#959;    &amp;omicron; &#959;    &omicron;    Greek small letter omicron<br /><br />&amp;#960;    &amp;pi;      &#960;    &pi;    Greek small letter pi<br />&amp;#961;    &amp;rho;     &#961;    &rho;    Greek small letter rho<br />&amp;#962;    &amp;sigmaf;  &#962;    &sigmaf;    Greek small letter sigma final<br />&amp;#963;    &amp;sigma;   &#963;    &sigma;    Greek small letter sigma<br />&amp;#964;    &amp;tau;     &#964;    &tau;    Greek small letter tau<br />&amp;#965;    &amp;upsilon; &#965;    &upsilon;    Greek small letter upsilon<br />&amp;#966;    &amp;phi;     &#966;    &phi;    Greek small letter phi<br />&amp;#967;    &amp;chi;     &#967;    &chi;    Greek small letter chi<br />&amp;#968;    &amp;psi;     &#968;    &psi;    Greek small letter psi<br />&amp;#969;    &amp;omega;   &#969;    &omega;    Greek small letter omega<br /> . . .<br /><br />&amp;#976;    ?       &#976;    &betac;    Greek curled beta<br />&amp;#977;    ?       &#977;    &thetas;    Greek script theta<br /> . . .<br />&amp;#981;    ?       &#981;    &phis;    Greek script phi<br />&amp;#982;    ?       &#982;    &omegapi;    Greek omega pi<br />&amp;#983;    ?       &#983;    &kai;    Greek kai symbol<br />&amp;#984;    ?       &#984;    &Stigma;    Greek capital stigma<br />&amp;#985;    ?       &#985;    &stigma;    Greek small letter stigma<br /> . . .<br />&amp;#1002;   ?       &#1002;    &Shima;    Coptic capital shima<br />&amp;#1003;   ?       &#1003;    &shima;    Coptic small letter shima<br /> . . .<br />&amp;#1006;   ?       &#1006;    &kappas;    Greek small script kappa<br />&amp;#1007;   ?       &#1007;    &rhot;    Greek small tailed rho<br /></pre><br /><br />There are miscellaneous characters of some possible use at the end of the Unicode Greek block.&nbsp;   None of those codes, such as &amp;#981; for a Greek script phi, produced useful character graphics in the display of those in my browser.&nbsp;  And none of the character entity names that I guessed accomplished anything either.<h3>Additional interesting symbols</h3>The following symbols are part of a general effort to find other useful goodies in the available Unicode fonts.&nbsp; I don't even have good guesses for entity character names, so I will show the Unicode code as well as the numeric entity code:<br /><br /><pre><br />&amp;#1488;   U+05D0    &#1488;    &aleph;    Hebrew letter alef<br /> . . .<br />&amp;#5139;   U+2013    &#5139;         En dash<br />&amp;#5140;   U+2014    &#5140;         Em dash<br />&amp;#5141;   U+2015    &#5141;         Quotation dash<br />&amp;#5142;   U+2016    &#5142;         Double vertical line<br />&amp;#5143;   U+2017    &#5143;         Double low line<br />&amp;#5144;   U+2018    &#5144;         Left single quote<br />&amp;#5145;   U+2019    &#5145;         Right single quote<br /> . . .<br />&amp;#5148;   U+201C    &#5148;         Left double quote<br />&amp;#5149;   U+201D    &#5149;         Right double quote<br /> . . .<br />&amp;#5152;   U+2020    &#5152;         dagger<br />&amp;#5153;   U+2021    &#5153;         double dagger<br />&amp;#5154;   U+2022    &#5154;    &dot;    dot<br />&amp;#5155;   U+2023    &#5155;         triangular dot<br />&amp;#5156;   U+2024    &#5156;         one-dot leader<br />&amp;#5157;   U+2025    &#5157;         two-dot leader<br />&amp;#5158;   U+2026    &#5158;         horizontal ellipse<br /> . . .<br /></pre><br /><br />There are other Unicodes to try out and see what can be reliably presented.<br /><br /><br>
